  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_879824034" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/879824034" />
    <a title="Nadine Jones" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/115626-nadine-jones"><img alt="Nadine Jones" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1180985415p2/115626.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/879824034?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nadine Jones" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nadine Jones" href="/user/show/115626-nadine-jones">Nadine Jones</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/115626-nadine-jones?shelf=fantasy-and-sci-fi">fantasy-and-sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer879824034" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7661735233644402101"><blockquote>
  <i>It was going to be all right. The contract, unwritten, between her and her society—Kenzo Yagai’s society, Roger Camden’s society—would hold. With dissent and strife and yes, some hatred. She suddenly thought of Tony’s beggars in Spain, furious at the strong because the beggars were not. Yes. But it would hold. <br/><br/>She believed that. <br/><br/>She did.</i>
</blockquote><br/><br/><br/>This came highly recommended, and I think my expectations were much too high. I was disappointed. Too many lengthy rambling philosophical asides, not enough </span>
  <span id="freeText7661735233644402101" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>It was going to be all right. The contract, unwritten, between her and her society—Kenzo Yagai’s society, Roger Camden’s society—would hold. With dissent and strife and yes, some hatred. She suddenly thought of Tony’s beggars in Spain, furious at the strong because the beggars were not. Yes. But it would hold. <br /><br />She believed that. <br /><br />She did.</i>
</blockquote><br /><br /><br />This came highly recommended, and I think my expectations were much too high. I was disappointed. Too many lengthy rambling philosophical asides, not enough story! I think if I had read this when I was younger, with lots of time to debate it over coffee and wine with friends, I would have liked it more.<br /><br />This started out great, what a premise! But it sagged in the middle, weighed down by a dull protagonist and excessive authorial philosophizing. Leisha is like some sort of Vulcan confused by human emotions, and that got old fast. Jennifer, her nemesis of a sort, is just too <i>too</i>. Too evil and insane and deluded, basically. I wasn't really that interested in either one of them, and for the most part I wasn't really interested, period. At one point I found myself playing Bejeweled rather than reading this book - bad sign. The ending grabbed my interest again, raising this to a 3 star read. Maybe.<br /><br />The story starts with an engaging what-if scenario: what if science figured out how to genetically modify human embryos to remove the physical need for sleep? How would that affect the person? How much more could you do with your life with those extra hours? How much could you learn and achieve? What are the potential side effects? How would the rest of the world behave? Would the Sleepless be accepted? admired? reviled? attacked? How might society change?<br /><br />The "Beggars in Spain" of the title refers to an ethical puzzle: what does the skilled wage-earner owe to a random beggar (in Spain or otherwise)? In other words: What do the Sleepless owe the rest of the world who are not as skilled as they are? What if the world resents them and attacks them?<br /><br />Some parts of this echo our present in the 2017 US a bit more strongly than I'd like. (From an editorial in the newspaper):<br /><blockquote>
  <i>The United States has never been a country that much values calm, logic, and rationality. We have, as a people, tended to label these things “cold.” We have, as a people, tended to admire feeling and action. We exalt in our stories and our memorials—not the creation of the Constitution but its defense at Iwo Jima; not the intellectual achievements of a Linus Pauling but the heroic passion of a Charles Lindbergh; not the inventors of the mono-rails and computers that unite us but the composers of the angry songs of rebellion that divide us. A peculiar aspect of this phenomenon is that it grows stronger in times of prosperity. The better off our citizenry, the greater their contempt for the calm reasoning that got them there, and the more passionate their indulgence in emotion. <br /></i>
</blockquote><br /><br />While these philosophical asides in the forms of editorials and inner monologues are interesting, I wish there was less of these and more story. Less tell, more show. Allow me to draw these conclusions myself.<br /><br />This was originally published as a novella, and I wonder if I would have found it much stronger in that shorter form, since my main complaint is that this was too long and rambling. Excise most of those philosophical rambles that are really just a fancy tell-don't-show, and I would find this to be a better book.<br /><br />Some notes :<br /><br />Part One starts in 2008, which was the "near future" at the time it was written, when Leisha is conceived. Part Two starts in 2051, when Leisha is in her 40s. Part Three starts in 2075. Part Four starts in 2091.<br /><br />Ms Kress does a nice job imagining the small technological advances of each age (hover cars, natch), but it's unfortunate that she chose to keep mentioning "modems." Each time the word appears, it drops like a rock in a pond, dragging down the imagined near future. Modems are now as out-dated as rotary phones! Word count for "modem" : 5. Mercifully, it only shows up in Part One. <br /><br />Argh! I hate gardening errors!! <br /><blockquote>
  <i>Alice, who loved gardening, had a fresh bouquet from her garden flown to Leisha’s apartment every single day, at a cost Jordan considered insane. And the flowers were ordinary, hardy garden blooms: phlox and sunflowers and day lilies and lemon-drop marigolds, which Leisha could have bought on the streets of Chicago</i>
</blockquote> <br />Nooooo .... no one would put daylilies in a bouquet! The flower only lasts (yep, you guessed it) one day! Plus, "daylily" is one word, not two (no matter what Goodread's spellcheck seems to think).</span>
  <a data-text-id="7661735233644402101" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


