<div id="review_160594622" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/160594622" />
    <a title="Maree" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5001811-maree"><img alt="Maree" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1304369647p2/5001811.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/160594622?book_show_action=true">Apr 12, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maree" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maree" href="/user/show/5001811-maree">Maree</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer160594622&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer160594622" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12283165165078488827">This story really felt like three in one with the three parts. I feel like I&apos;ve already read the trilogy...what else could possibly happen? We&apos;ve skipped through three generations, which is more than most trilogies tackle. But I suppose since <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[ the Sleepless can never die of old age <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> then it&apos;s not as big a deal to skip around the years.<br/><br/>The novel brings up a lot of issues such as jealousy and hate over something you don&apos;t quite understand in the beginning. It was real</span>
  <span id="freeText12283165165078488827" style="display:none">This story really felt like three in one with the three parts. I feel like I've already read the trilogy...what else could possibly happen? We've skipped through three generations, which is more than most trilogies tackle. But I suppose since <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ the Sleepless can never die of old age <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> then it's not as big a deal to skip around the years.<br /><br />The novel brings up a lot of issues such as jealousy and hate over something you don't quite understand in the beginning. It was really interesting to see how the views of the general public changed over the years, from jealousy and hate crimes over Sleepless ability to it not really making a difference because they're off floating somewhere in the sky. But shunning and hatred because other people are smarter or better isn't the way to go in my book. But of course, we have the inside view of the Sleepless and can relate to them because we see that they're like us. In books, people tend to assume they would have the same special abilities in fantasy and scifi books as the main characters (like Luke having the force, Harry having magic). But if we were actually Sleepers and the market was being cornered by Sleepless, how would we feel? I know if I went to school with someone who had the advantage of being able to study all night without that crash in the morning, I'd be not only jealous but resentful. But how does this really differ from people who are just smarter in general? They always are begrudged by people less intelligent than them. I think the difference with the Sleepless is that there is a clear line drawn in the sand, and no borderline that can be accepted. So in this way, I feel the novel was very honestly written in regard to people's reactions to the Sleepless.<br /><br />I was intrigued about the way society worked in the second half of the novel with the Livers and the mules who got everything done. I was surprised that 80% of the population managed to be Livers; I didn't think they'd have enough money for it if they weren't doing anything. And I suppose it all eventually collapses, so fair enough. But I think this is very much the way society works today for the elite few who can buy their votes but care for nothing but their pleasure yacht races. It's just not 80% of the population.<br /><br />Drew was an interesting character I didn't really know what to do with. I'm assuming he comes up more in later books, as he didn't seem to do much for the story here. Anyone could have learned the trick to make Miri and the others lucid dream; I'm not sure why it had to be someone close to the family.<br /><br />I think the most interesting person was obviously Leisha and the way she stuck to her guns on law for so long before giving up. And Jennifer was just crazy about staying on top of everything. I had thought that she had a bunch of money growing up and was therefore never harmed or abused by Sleepers, so I'm not really sure what prompted her undisguised hatred of all Sleepers, aside from maybe Tony's death. But I thought she needed something a little more traumatizing to be so intensely out of control.<br /><br />The thought strings for the supers were cool, and I liked their part in shutting down Jennifer, though I didn't really understand why they stood down at the end and needed Leisha's help in getting out when they had control of everything.<br /><br />Lastly, for my random thoughts, I thought the beggar metaphor was used far too much throughout. If you name the book that, then we know it's significant, it doesn't need to keep being shoved into our faces.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12283165165078488827" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


